The dataset was conducted 3.12.2014 - 10.1.2015 and created 2015 by Teachers’ Academy funding for Kimmo Vehkalahti. THis is the data obtained from international survey of the students taking Introduction to Social Statistics, fall 2014 (in Finnish) course. Data set of Kimmo measures Approaches to Learning. I kept variables of interest for my exercise.

The information on the initial dataset can be found in the following link: https://www.mv.helsinki.fi/home/kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS3-meta.txt

In my datset, I have 7 dimentions accordingly to the numnder of variables.
Variables names and short descriptions of my dataset:

age - age (in years) derived from the date of birth
attitude - Global attitude toward statistics
points - Exam points
gender - Gender: M (Male), F (Female)
stra - Scores of students on startegic learning referring to the way how students organize their studies. Computed variable
surf - Scores of students on surface learning referring to the memorizing without understanding, with lack of personal engagement way of studing. Computed variable
deep - Scores of students on deep learning referring to intention to understand better, with a true commitment to work during studies. Computed variable

Information about creating the computed variables is found in: http://www.helsinki.fi/~kvehkala/JYTmooc/JYTOPKYS2-meta.txt

Some additional information on the variables can be found in the following link: https://www.slideshare.net/kimmovehkalahti/the-relationship-between-learning-approaches-and-students-achievements-in-an-introductory-statistics-course-in-finland

Regression model

We will create a regression model with attitude, strategic learning and deep learning as explanatory variables and points as dependents variable. We have chosen strategic learning and deep learning over surface learning since deep learning has strong negative correlation with surface learning, and thus, it will not explain the model significantly more.

model <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + deep, data = data)
summary(model)

From the summary output we can see that the affect of attitude on dependent variable points is statistically significant (beta = 0.3, st.error = 0.05, p < 0.05). Meanwhile, strategic learning and deep learning don`t give statistically significant effect on the points (p > 0.05).

I have run the model few times with each independent variable separately, but none of them except attitude had statistically significant effect on the dependent variable, therefore we excluded them. I will remove non-significant independent variables from the model.

model <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = data)
summary(model)

After, we fit the model again with just attitude as independent variable, we explain the summary of the model: the affect of attitude on dependent variable points is statistically significant (beta = 0.3, st.error = 0.05, p < 0.05). For the further research, we wold use just an attitude variable as an independent variable.

Model interpretation

R Squared is showing proportion of variance in the dependent variable that can be explained by the independent variables. Adjusted R squared is modified version of R2 that was adjusted for the number of predictors in the model. Looking at the output of the model, I can conclude that the model explains 19% of the proportion of the variance or 18.6% for Adjusted R Squared.

The equation for the model is “points = 8.97 + (0.353 * “attitude”). The model is statistically significant (p < 0.05). The model shows that with the increase of attitude by 1, the points that can be gotten are increasing by 0.353 and the point value would be 9.323.

Basically, people who have bigger score of attitude tent to get better points on the final exam.

Model validation

model <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = data)
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model, which = c(1,2,5))

Looking at the Residual vs Fitted plot, I can say that there is no any pattern in how the residuals are spreaded. Normal Q-Q plot shows that the fit to the normal distribution is reasonable as point follow the line. Looking at the Residuals vs Leverage plot, we conclude that there is no single observation that stands out significantly that meant that there are no single observation that strongly affect the fit line.

Therefore, I assume that the model meet assumptions.

Information on dataset

The dataset was merged form two datasets taken from UCI Machine learning repository: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Student+Performance.

The initial datasets approach student achievement in secondary education, providing the data on the performance in two subjects: Mathematics (mat) and Portuguese language (por). The data was collected by using school reports and questionnaires.

A new datset includes only the observations from students present in both datasets (inner_join function), and it was joined using all other variables than “failures”, “paid”, “absences”, “G1”, “G2”, “G3”. To combine the ‘duplicated’ answers in the joined data I took rounded average of each row of the two columns for numeric column vectors and took first column vector for not numeric column vectors.

Also, new variables were added: ‘alc_use’ as the average of ‘Dalc’ and ‘Walc’ and ‘high_use’ is TRUE if ‘alc_use’ is higher than 2 and FALSE otherwise.

Variable information:

1 school - student’s school (binary: ‘GP’ - Gabriel Pereira or ‘MS’ - Mousinho da Silveira)
2 sex - student’s sex (binary: ‘F’ - female or ‘M’ - male)
3 age - student’s age (numeric: from 15 to 22)
4 address - student’s home address type (binary: ‘U’ - urban or ‘R’ - rural)
5 famsize - family size (binary: ‘LE3’ - less or equal to 3 or ‘GT3’ - greater than 3)
6 Pstatus - parent’s cohabitation status (binary: ‘T’ - living together or ‘A’ - apart)
7 Medu - mother’s education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 â€“ 5th to 9th grade, 3 â€“ secondary education or 4 â€“ higher education)
8 Fedu - father’s education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 â€“ 5th to 9th grade, 3 â€“ secondary education or 4 â€“ higher education)
9 Mjob - mother’s job (nominal: ‘teacher’, ‘health’ care related, civil ‘services’ (e.g. administrative or police), ‘at_home’ or ‘other’)
10 Fjob - father’s job (nominal: ‘teacher’, ‘health’ care related, civil ‘services’ (e.g. administrative or police), ‘at_home’ or ‘other’)
11 reason - reason to choose this school (nominal: close to ‘home’, school ‘reputation’, ‘course’ preference or ‘other’)
12 guardian - student’s guardian (nominal: ‘mother’, ‘father’ or ‘other’)
13 traveltime - home to school travel time (numeric: 1 - <15 min., 2 - 15 to 30 min., 3 - 30 min. to 1 hour, or 4 - >1 hour)
14 studytime - weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours)
15 failures - average, number of past class failures (numeric: n if 1<=n<3, else 4)
16 schoolsup - extra educational support (binary: yes or no)
17 famsup - family educational support (binary: yes or no)
18 paid - first, extra paid classes within the course subject (Math or Portuguese) (binary: yes or no)
19 activities - extra-curricular activities (binary: yes or no)
20 nursery - attended nursery school (binary: yes or no)
21 higher - wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no)
22 internet - Internet access at home (binary: yes or no)
23 romantic - with a romantic relationship (binary: yes or no)
24 famrel - quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent)
25 freetime - free time after school (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
26 goout - going out with friends (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
27 Dalc - workday alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
28 Walc - weekend alcohol consumption (numeric: from 1 - very low to 5 - very high)
29 health - current health status (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - very good)
30 absences - average, number of school absences (numeric: from 0 to 93)
31 G1 - average, first period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
31 G2 - average, second period grade (numeric: from 0 to 20)
32 G3 - average, final grade (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)
33 alc_use - average weekday and weekend alcohol consumption (numeric)
34 high_use - logical, if average weekday and weekend alcohol consumption is high (> 2) (logical: T, F)
Common variables fro the initial datasets that were not used for joining:
35 G1.m - first period grade in Mathematics (numeric: from 0 to 20)
36 G2.m - second period grade in Mathematics (numeric: from 0 to 20)
37 G3.m - final grade in Mathematics (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)
38 G1.p - first period grade in Portuguese (numeric: from 0 to 20)
39 G2.p - second period grade in Portuguese(numeric: from 0 to 20)
40 G3.p - final grade in Portuguese (numeric: from 0 to 20, output target)
41 paid.m - extra paid classes within the course subject Math (binary: yes or no)
42 paid.p - extra paid classes within the course subject Portuguese (binary: yes or no)
43 failures.m - number of past class failures in Mathematics (numeric: n if 1<=n<3, else 4)
44 failures.p - number of past class failures in Portuguese (numeric: n if 1<=n<3, else 4)
45 absences.m - number of school absences in Mathematics (numeric: from 0 to 93)
46 absences.p - number of school absences in Portuguese (numeric: from 0 to 93)

Using the datase we will study the relationships between high/low odds of alcohol consumption and 1) quality of family relationships (“famrel” -categorical), 2) frequency of hanging out with friends (“goout” -categorical), 3) number of school absences (“absences” -continuous), 4) free time after school (“freetime” - continuous).

Hypothesis

I will present my hypothesis about association with alcohol consumption for each chosen variable:
1) “famrel”: students with the worse relationship in a family have higher odd of high alcohol consumption;
2) “goout”: the more go out with friend, the higher odds og high alcohol consumption;
3) “absences”: students with bigger number of school absences are more likely to have higher odds of high alcohol consumption;
4) “freetime”: the more free time after school, the higher odds of high alcohol consumption.

Firstly, I will evaluate distribution for the chosen categorical variables. We can see that both people with high and low alcohol consumption think that relations in their family are good (median is 4, high_use vs famrel). However the distributions are skewed, and we can see that more people who have low alcohol consumption tend to believe that relation in their family are excellent (5, distribution skewed to the right) while more of people with high level of alcohol consumption tend to think that relation in their family fall to average level (3, distribution skewed to the left). Therefore, people who have worse family relation tend to drink more. The results confirms the hypothesis.

On the second boxplot, hight_use vs freetime, we can see that plots are the same, thus I can not confirm the hypothesis.

On the plot for absences, we can see that median for two groups of people are almost the same, but the distribution is skewed to the right for “heavy drinkers”, also, maximum is higher for them. It makes us assume, that the hypothesis was right and “heavy drinkers” have more abscesses.

On the lats boxplot, high_use vs goout, the median for pope with low level of alcohol consumption is on the average level (3) and the distribution is skewed to the left with maximum at 4. Meanwhile, median for people with high alcohol consumption is referring to high probability of going out (4) with maximum at very high probability of going out (5). Therefore, I can confirm the hypothesis claiming that people who go out more often have higher odds of high alcohol consumption.

Logistic regression model

Before conducting the analysis, I indicate that freetime, famrel and goout are categorical factors, thus, I should threat them as factors here.

data$freetime = as.factor(data$freetime)

In the output we can find odds ratios and their confidence intervals.There are no statistically significant results for freetime variable as CI cross 1, thus, association is not significant.
CI for OR of absences are statistically significant. OR = 1.08, thus, the model shows that with the increase for absences, the odds of high alcohol use are increasing.
Goout1 (the probability to go out is very low) is the reference category for goout variable. CI fro OR of goout4 and goout5 are significant (not crossing 1): participants who has high probability to go out (goout4), have 6.09-fold odds being “heavy drinkers” in comparison to people who have very low probability to go out (goout1). Similary, participants who has very high probability to go out (goout5), have 10.58-fold odds being “heavy drinkers”.
The rest of the categories are not statistically significant. Finding for the significant cases confirmed the hypothesis regarding association of absences and going out with friend with the odds of having high alcohol consumption level.

The confusion matrix shows that 61 and 31 results were bredicted faulty. As (61 + 31)/380 = 0.24, 24% of the predictions were faulty. Next step is to compute the total proportion of inaccurately classified individuals.

# define a loss function (average prediction error)
loss_func <- function(class, prob) {
  n_wrong <- abs(class - prob) > 0.5
  mean(n_wrong)
}

# call loss_func to compute the average number of wrong predictions in the (training) data
loss_func(class = data$high_use, prob = data$probability)
## [1] 0.2486486
# random guess
mean(data$high_use)
## [1] 0.3

Evaluation the results, we can say that the model misclassifices 25% of the training cases.
The random guess will give 30% mistake if we guess that every person does not have high alcohol consumption. Meanwhile, the model would have 25% mistake. That means that model is just slightly better than the random guess.

Data has one integer (rad), one dichotomous (chas) and the rest are numeric variables.
Name of the dataset is “Housing Values in Suburbs of Boston”. Dataset has 506 observations and 14 variables. It describes housing Values in Suburbs of Boston.
This data frame contains the following columns:

crim - per capita crime rate by town.
zn - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
indus - proportion of non-retail business acres per town.
chas - Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise).
nox - nitrogen oxides concentration (parts per 10 million).
rm - average number of rooms per dwelling.
age - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940.
dis - weighted mean of distances to five Boston employment centres.
rad - index of accessibility to radial highways.
tax - full-value property-tax rate per $10,000.
ptratio - pupil-teacher ratio by town.
black - 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town.
lstat - lower status of the population (percent).
medv - median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s.

Sources of the dataset:
1) Harrison, D. and Rubinfeld, D.L. (1978) Hedonic prices and the demand for clean air. J. Environ. Economics and Management 5, 81–102.
2) Belsley D.A., Kuh, E. and Welsch, R.E. (1980) Regression Diagnostics. Identifying Influential Data and Sources of Collinearity. New York: Wiley.

More information about the variables in the Boston dataset can be found by the following link: https://stat.ethz.ch/R-manual/R-devel/library/MASS/html/Boston.html.

# the function for lda biplot arrows
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}

# target classes as numeric
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)

# plot the lda results
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 3)

# save and remove crime categories
test_correct = test$crim
test$crim = NULL

Descriptions on the data

The data is a joined data set of Human Development Index and Gender Development Index that is originated from the United Nations Development Programme’s website. Source of the data: http://hdr.undp.org/en/content/human-development-index-hdi.
The data has the following variables:

  1. hdirank = HDI ranking for countries
  2. Country = Country name
  3. hdi = Human Development Index (HDI)
  4. lifeexp = Life expectancy at birth
  5. expedu = Expected years of schooling
  6. meanedu = Mean years of schooling
  7. gni = Gross National Income (GNI) per capita
  8. gni-hdi = GNI per capita rank minus HDI rank
  9. giirank = GII ranking for countries
  10. gii = Gender Inequality Index (GII)
  11. matmor = Maternal mortality ratio
  12. adobirth = Adolescent birth rate
  13. repparl = Percetange of female representatives in parliament
  14. edu2F = Proportion of females with at least secondary education
  15. edu2M = Proportion of males with at least secondary education
  16. labfF = Proportion of females in the labour force
  17. labfM = Proportion of males in the labour force
  18. edu2FM - the ratio of Female and Male populations with secondary education in each country (2eduF / 2eduM)
  19. labfFM = the ratio of labour force participation of females and males in each country (labfF / labfM).

Correlations:
1) Positive:
- lifeexp and edu2FM (r = 0.710), a large correlation shows that in countries with beigger life expectancy at birth there is begger ratio of Female and Male populations with secondary education
- expeedu and edu2FM (r = 0.778), the correlation shows that the bigger expected years of schooling, the bigger ratio of Female and Male populations with secondary education
- gni and eduFM (0.542), a moderate correlation shows that in countries with bigger Gross National Income (GNI) per capita there is bigger ratio of Female and Male populations with secondary education
- expeedu and lifeexp (r = 0.789), a large correlation shows that in countries with bigger Expected years of schooling, life expectancy at birth is bigger
- gni and lifeexp (r = 0.627), a moderate correlation shows that in countries that have bigger Gross National Income (GNI) per capita, life expectancy at birth is higher
- adobirth and matmor (r = 0.759), the large association shows that in countries with higher Adolescent birth rate, Maternal mortality ratio is higher

  1. Negative
  • matmor and edu2FM (r = -0.707), a large correlation shows that in countries where Maternal mortality ratio is bigger, ratio of Female and Male populations with secondary education is smaller
  • adobirth and edu2FM (-0.690), a large correlation shows that in countries with higher Adolescent birth rate, the ratio of Female and Male populations with secondary education is smaller
  • expeedu and matmor/adobirth (r = -0.736, r = -0.704), large associations shows that in countries with higher Eexpected years of schooling, Maternal mortality ratio and Adolescent birth rate are smaller
  • gni and matmor/adobirth (r = -0.495 and r = -0.577), moderate correlation shows that in countries with higer Gross National Income (GNI) per capita, Maternal mortality ratio and Adolescent birth rate are smaller
    The correlations are statistically significnat.

# visualize MCA
plot(MCA, invisible=c("ind"), habillage = "quali", graph.type = "classic")

All the dimensions explain quite equal amount of variation. To explain 50% of variation we will need 6 dimensions. We are suggested to have 3 dimensions, where the first one would explain sex; second - age_Q, How; third - how, frequency; healthy is almost equaly explained by first and second clusters. Therefore, we can say that if people dring tea alone or with milk or lemon, it is correlated to age; frequency is correlated to the way people make tea (bag or not).
The distance between the categories tells us how similar they are. Therefore, 25-34 y.o. people prefer unpackged tea 1 tim per day. The majority of 25-35 people t=whoo are drinking tea are males. Females prefer to drink tea 2 times per day and more likely to drink tea made of tea bag. People from 35 to 44 and from 45 to 59 tend to drink bag tea and believe that it is healthy to drink tea. The older people the more they tend to drink tea with lemon or milk. Also, old peopel are more likely to believe that to drink tea is healthy. Category “other” is obvious outliner.
